  "chunk_index": 36,
  "summary": "Bündel expresses her disdain for George Lomax to Lorelai, explaining that she fled his proposal by escaping through a window. Lord Kettlemere joins them, and Bündel accuses her father of encouraging George's advances. After a brief game of golf, the group returns to the house to find a note from George addressed to Lord Chiltern. In the note, George describes Bündel's \"girlish confusion\" following his proposal as attractive and expresses confidence that he will eventually win her over, a sentiment that shocks Lord Kettlemere.\n\nThe situation changes when Bündel receives an urgent telephone call from Jimmy Sycamore. Jimmy claims that Bill has discovered something that could be the \"biggest scoop of the century\" and instructs Bündel and Lorelai to come to the Seven Dials Club in town. He advises them to use the excuse that they are taking Lorelai home and to find a way to bypass the doorman, Alfred. Bündel informs her father of their departure and drives Lorelai to London.\n\nUpon arriving at 14 Hanover Street, Bündel tells Alfred that the police are looking for Mosgrove and gives him ten pounds to flee, ensuring he will not interfere with their meeting. Jimmy and Bill arrive, and Jimmy leads the group into a room containing seven chairs around a table and various glassware. As Jimmy prepares to investigate a cabinet, Lorelai rushes back up the stairs in a panic. She informs the group that Bill is in the car and believes he is dead because he is not moving or speaking.",
